1
00:00:34,618 --> 00:00:35,911
Babe, what are you doing?

2
00:00:35,994 --> 00:00:37,663
I'm looking for the aloe iodine.

3
00:00:37,746 --> 00:00:39,414
It's not here.

4
00:00:39,497 --> 00:00:41,583
Yeah, because that's not where it is.

5
00:00:43,877 --> 00:00:45,545
Babe, c-can you give me 12 seconds,

6
00:00:45,629 --> 00:00:46,939
and I will come and get it for you?

7
00:00:46,963 --> 00:00:48,799
Twelve seconds is specific.

8
00:00:49,549 --> 00:00:51,176
Wow, these are very expired.

9
00:01:06,775 --> 00:01:08,610
Hmm.

10
00:01:08,694 --> 00:01:11,613
Okay. Betadine. Chlorhexidine.

11
00:01:11,697 --> 00:01:13,323
No iodine.

12
00:01:14,115 --> 00:01:16,952
Oh. Right. Thanks.

13
00:01:29,255 --> 00:01:30,256
But...

14
00:01:30,966 --> 00:01:32,050
Well, that's not...

15
00:01:33,635 --> 00:01:34,636
We tried for two years.

16
00:01:34,720 --> 00:01:37,055
I know. I know, babe.

17
00:01:37,555 --> 00:01:39,517
I mean, we don't wanna even
talk about it anymore.

18
00:01:39,557 --> 00:01:41,768
Talking was not the important part.

19
00:01:43,770 --> 00:01:46,648
It wasn't gonna be for us,
and we were okay with that.

20
00:01:46,732 --> 00:01:49,109
- We were okay, but...
- Mm-hmm.

21
00:01:51,152 --> 00:01:52,320
Well...

22
00:01:55,406 --> 00:01:56,407
This is better.

23
00:01:57,367 --> 00:01:59,327
Yes. It's...

24
00:01:59,410 --> 00:02:02,038
- It's a lot better, isn't it?
- This is great.

25
00:02:13,967 --> 00:02:16,863
Obviously, we're gonna need protocols
to account for our cell mutations...

26
00:02:16,887 --> 00:02:17,721
No, Reed.

27
00:02:17,804 --> 00:02:19,445
monitoring for further cosmic effects.

28
00:02:19,472 --> 00:02:20,473
Reed.

29
00:02:20,556 --> 00:02:22,058
We can do this.

30
00:02:23,101 --> 00:02:24,477
Okay?

31
00:02:24,560 --> 00:02:26,187
I really want to do this.

32
00:02:26,271 --> 00:02:27,731
I really want to do this.

33
00:02:29,024 --> 00:02:30,066
Then what?

34
00:02:34,988 --> 00:02:37,032
Nothing is going to change.

35
00:02:38,449 --> 00:02:39,659
Of course not.

36
00:02:42,120 --> 00:02:43,955
<i>Ladies and gentlemen,</i>

37
00:02:44,039 --> 00:02:46,833
<i>we welcome you to a very special event</i>

38
00:02:46,917 --> 00:02:50,461
<i>celebrating four years of
the Fantastic Four.</i>

39
00:02:50,545 --> 00:02:54,215
<i>And now your host
for the evening, Ted Gilbert.</i>

40
00:02:54,299 --> 00:02:56,634
Well, now, folks.

41
00:02:56,718 --> 00:02:59,220
Folks, we all know the story.

42
00:02:59,304 --> 00:03:02,223
Four brave astronauts head up into space,

43
00:03:02,307 --> 00:03:04,267
encounter a bit of cosmic turbulence,

44
00:03:04,350 --> 00:03:05,852
and come back forever changed.

45
00:03:05,936 --> 00:03:08,188
Not just the molecules of their bodies

46
00:03:08,271 --> 00:03:10,148
but also their place in our hearts.

47
00:03:10,648 --> 00:03:12,025
And, now, a look back.

48
00:03:12,108 --> 00:03:14,070
<i>This is </i>Excelsior<i> Launch Control.</i>

49
00:03:14,152 --> 00:03:16,571
<i>T-minus 3 hours, 42 minutes, 19 seconds.</i>

50
00:03:16,654 --> 00:03:18,364
<i>Four years ago,</i>

51
00:03:18,448 --> 00:03:21,576
<i>man and woman conquered
the last frontier as we know it,</i>

52
00:03:22,202 --> 00:03:24,495
<i>the exploration of space.</i>

53
00:03:25,997 --> 00:03:27,516
The best pilot in the world right here.

54
00:03:27,540 --> 00:03:29,793
Yeah. The best-looking he means.

55
00:03:32,879 --> 00:03:36,007
{\an8}<i>It was my
mission: Space exploration.</i>

56
00:03:36,507 --> 00:03:39,219
{\an8}<i>I assembled the best scientific minds
to come along,</i>

57
00:03:39,302 --> 00:03:41,512
<i>who also happened to be
my best friend,</i>

58
00:03:42,222 --> 00:03:43,473
<i>my wife</i>

59
00:03:43,556 --> 00:03:45,141
<i>and my brother-in-law.</i>

60
00:03:45,641 --> 00:03:47,643
Comms check. Everybody, sound off.

61
00:03:47,727 --> 00:03:49,395
- Check.
- Check, check.

62
00:03:49,479 --> 00:03:51,022
- Check.
- Comms are live.

63
00:03:51,689 --> 00:03:52,834
That last voice you just heard

64
00:03:52,858 --> 00:03:54,442
was my baby brother, Jonathan Storm,

65
00:03:54,525 --> 00:03:57,863
and, ladies, he is very single.

66
00:03:58,864 --> 00:04:00,782
- Kiss for luck.
- Kiss?

67
00:04:03,368 --> 00:04:05,536
<i>However,</i>
<i>Dr. Richards's expedition</i>

68
00:04:05,620 --> 00:04:08,123
<i>encountered an unforeseen event</i>

69
00:04:08,206 --> 00:04:10,041
<i>that changed not only the lives</i>

70
00:04:10,125 --> 00:04:11,435
<i>of these courageous individuals...</i>

71
00:04:11,459 --> 00:04:12,603
<i>Verify go for launch.</i>

72
00:04:12,627 --> 00:04:13,771
<i>Go for launch.</i>

73
00:04:13,795 --> 00:04:16,256
<i>...but also</i>
<i>the course of our history.</i>

74
00:04:16,339 --> 00:04:18,461
- <i>Come in, </i>Excelsior.
<i>- What is that?</i>

75
00:04:18,508 --> 00:04:19,830
<i>I don't know. I don't know.</i>

76
00:04:20,468 --> 00:04:22,637
<i>It must be the cosmic rays.</i>

77
00:04:22,720 --> 00:04:24,597
- <i>Ben! Ben!</i>
<i>- Ben!</i>

78
00:04:25,681 --> 00:04:27,475
Obviously, while we were in space

79
00:04:27,558 --> 00:04:28,768
due to errors on my part...

80
00:04:28,852 --> 00:04:30,020
- Stop.
- we encountered

81
00:04:30,103 --> 00:04:32,355
a cosmic storm that altered our DNA.

82
00:04:32,438 --> 00:04:34,291
<i>Rescue in progress</i>
<i>of the </i>Excelsior <i>launch.</i>

83
00:04:34,315 --> 00:04:35,984
We came back with anomalies.

84
00:04:38,194 --> 00:04:40,947
<i>And they</i>
<i>returned with superpowers.</i>

85
00:04:51,958 --> 00:04:54,252
<i>They became our protectors.</i>

86
00:05:02,385 --> 00:05:03,594
Cannonball!

87
00:05:17,692 --> 00:05:19,903
<i>It's clobberin' time!</i>

88
00:05:32,874 --> 00:05:33,875
Hmm.

89
00:05:45,053 --> 00:05:47,305
I was at the opening of the Pan Am Tower

90
00:05:47,388 --> 00:05:49,015
when Mole Man attacked.

91
00:05:49,099 --> 00:05:52,393
<i>The Fantastic Four saved my life.</i>

92
00:06:04,906 --> 00:06:07,283
<i>Mole Man's attempt</i>
<i>to steal the Pan Am building</i>

93
00:06:07,367 --> 00:06:09,619
<i>was thwarted by the Fantastic Four.</i>

94
00:06:09,702 --> 00:06:11,746
This is all
Reed Richards's fault.

95
00:06:11,829 --> 00:06:14,249
Him and his endless pursuit of progress.

96
00:06:15,125 --> 00:06:16,667
Power to the underground!

97
00:06:20,964 --> 00:06:22,233
<i>And when the Mad Thinker</i>

98
00:06:22,257 --> 00:06:25,010
<i>tried to sabotage New York City</i>

99
00:06:25,718 --> 00:06:28,346
<i>the Fantastic Four came to our rescue.</i>

100
00:06:30,181 --> 00:06:31,224
Gotcha!

101
00:06:34,852 --> 00:06:35,853
Have a great day!

102
00:06:38,481 --> 00:06:40,066
<i>They defeated Red Ghost</i>

103
00:06:40,150 --> 00:06:41,859
<i>and his Super-Apes.</i>

104
00:06:52,495 --> 00:06:54,956
<i>They became our inspiration.</i>

105
00:06:55,040 --> 00:06:58,960
This equation not only confirms
alternate dimensions,

106
00:06:59,044 --> 00:07:01,087
but it suggests parallel Earths

107
00:07:01,171 --> 00:07:03,589
exist on different dimensional planes.

108
00:07:06,259 --> 00:07:07,843
Who wants to see a big explosion?

109
00:07:07,927 --> 00:07:09,179
Me!

110
00:07:11,306 --> 00:07:13,058
<i>And they became our leaders.</i>

111
00:07:13,141 --> 00:07:17,270
<i> Sue Storm brokers peace deal</i>
<i>with Harvey "Mole Man" Elder,</i>

112
00:07:17,353 --> 00:07:20,398
<i>leader of the underground
nation, Subterranea.</i>

113
00:07:20,481 --> 00:07:22,043
I don't trust surface dwellers.

114
00:07:22,108 --> 00:07:23,151
I never have.

115
00:07:23,234 --> 00:07:25,653
But I do trust Sue.

116
00:07:25,736 --> 00:07:29,865
We have come together today
to form a new charter,

117
00:07:29,949 --> 00:07:31,409
the Future Foundation.

118
00:07:31,492 --> 00:07:33,786
All participating countries agree

119
00:07:33,869 --> 00:07:36,622
to dismantle their armed forces.

120
00:07:36,706 --> 00:07:39,709
<i>And on this fourth anniversary,</i>
<i>we celebrate them.</i>

121
00:07:39,792 --> 00:07:41,961
<i>They are the very best of us.</i>

122
00:07:42,045 --> 00:07:44,505
<i>They are the Fantastic Four.</i>

123
00:07:44,589 --> 00:07:48,051
Thank you, Fantastic Four!

124
00:07:48,134 --> 00:07:49,177
Thank you, Fantastic Four!

125
00:07:49,260 --> 00:07:51,502
- Thank you, Fantastic Four!
- We love you, Fantastic Four.

126
00:07:51,554 --> 00:07:53,389
- I love you, Johnny!
- We love you!

127
00:07:53,473 --> 00:07:56,976
- Thank you, Fantastic Four.
- Thank you, Fantastic Four.

128
00:07:58,436 --> 00:08:03,108
We are proud to call them our guides,
our protectors and our friends.

129
00:08:03,191 --> 00:08:06,652
Let's hear it for Reed, Sue,
Johnny and Ben.

130
00:08:14,994 --> 00:08:16,555
I must say,
that was all a bit aggrandizing.

131
00:08:16,579 --> 00:08:18,221
- Yeah.
- H.E.R.B.I.E.

132
00:08:18,289 --> 00:08:19,433
H.E.R.B.I.E. with the herbs.

133
00:08:19,457 --> 00:08:21,393
How's that sauce looking?

134
00:08:21,417 --> 00:08:23,753
Don't do that.
Wash your hands first, please.

135
00:08:23,836 --> 00:08:25,147
I was wearing my gloves the whole time.

136
00:08:25,171 --> 00:08:26,692
Just wash your hands. Let me try that.

137
00:08:29,259 --> 00:08:30,510
Okay.

138
00:08:31,386 --> 00:08:34,597
Okay. Is this guy good?

139
00:08:34,680 --> 00:08:36,974
That is fantastic.

140
00:08:37,517 --> 00:08:39,185
- Oh, let me try.
- It's incredible stuff.

141
00:08:39,269 --> 00:08:40,353
Stop. Don't do that.

142
00:08:40,936 --> 00:08:42,938
Don't do that. It's not quite done.

143
00:08:43,022 --> 00:08:44,149
No, it's not quite done.

144
00:08:44,232 --> 00:08:45,650
No, it could be done,

145
00:08:45,733 --> 00:08:47,169
but I'm gonna add a little more garlic.

146
00:08:47,193 --> 00:08:48,444
Not because it's not delicious.

147
00:08:48,528 --> 00:08:50,696
I just want to add
a little bit of zip, okay?

148
00:08:56,077 --> 00:08:57,078
What are you doing?

149
00:08:57,620 --> 00:08:59,205
What do you mean, what am I doing?

150
00:08:59,289 --> 00:09:00,890
I mean, you're gonna ruin your appetite.

151
00:09:00,956 --> 00:09:03,334
I'm hungry.

152
00:09:05,378 --> 00:09:07,380
They're never late for Sunday dinner.

153
00:09:07,463 --> 00:09:08,964
Should we wait?

154
00:09:09,048 --> 00:09:10,966
I guess.

155
00:09:11,050 --> 00:09:12,260
You're late.

156
00:09:14,512 --> 00:09:15,930
What, uh... What do you mean?

157
00:09:16,013 --> 00:09:17,158
What do you mean, what do I mean?

158
00:09:17,182 --> 00:09:18,266
You're late for dinner.

159
00:09:18,349 --> 00:09:20,059
Oh. Yes, we are. We're late for dinner.

160
00:09:20,143 --> 00:09:21,784
- By a single minute.
- Yes, we were just...

161
00:09:21,852 --> 00:09:24,522
I had to put some aloe iodine
on my shoulder and...

162
00:09:24,605 --> 00:09:26,041
...just had to do
his shoulder and...

163
00:09:26,065 --> 00:09:27,918
Why is there breakfast cereal
on the dinner table?

164
00:09:27,942 --> 00:09:29,235
Why are you being weird?

165
00:09:29,777 --> 00:09:32,280
- We're not being weird.
- We're not acting weird.

166
00:09:32,363 --> 00:09:34,383
You're doing that
weird thing with your face.

167
00:09:34,407 --> 00:09:36,449
Well, we don't know
what you're talking about.

168
00:09:39,204 --> 00:09:40,205
Are you pregnant?

169
00:09:45,918 --> 00:09:47,837
- Yeah, we're pregnant.
- Yes, yes.

170
00:09:47,920 --> 00:09:48,921
How did you know that?

171
00:09:49,004 --> 00:09:50,316
Have you looked at your husband's face?

172
00:09:50,340 --> 00:09:52,217
I know.
He just cannot keep a secret.

173
00:09:52,300 --> 00:09:54,302
- Wait, what? Really?
- Yeah.

174
00:09:55,845 --> 00:09:58,598
What?

175
00:09:58,681 --> 00:10:02,685
You are gonna be the best mom.
Oh, my God.

176
00:10:02,768 --> 00:10:04,604
And you are gonna be the best dad.

177
00:10:04,687 --> 00:10:06,897
Just kidding. You are out of your depth.

178
00:10:06,981 --> 00:10:09,609
But we... we're gonna be
the best uncles ever.

179
00:10:11,068 --> 00:10:12,445
Okay, we should eat.

180
00:10:14,322 --> 00:10:16,031
You're handling this well, you know.

181
00:10:16,115 --> 00:10:19,160
I figured you'd be locked in your lab
drenched in a panic sweat.

182
00:10:19,827 --> 00:10:21,454
I have that scheduled for later.

183
00:10:22,121 --> 00:10:24,039
Countdown continues

184
00:10:24,123 --> 00:10:25,750
as the Fantastic Four
prepare to welcome

185
00:10:25,833 --> 00:10:27,835
a new member to the family.

186
00:10:27,918 --> 00:10:31,214
<i>Needless to say,
preparations inside the Baxter Building</i>

187
00:10:31,297 --> 00:10:33,591
<i>are well underway.</i>

188
00:10:33,674 --> 00:10:36,719
All right, H.E.R.B.I.E.,
let's start the baby prep.

189
00:10:55,070 --> 00:10:57,948
H.E.R.B.I.E.!

190
00:11:03,454 --> 00:11:04,681
<i>Yancy Street bookies</i>

191
00:11:04,705 --> 00:11:06,874
<i>are putting the odds of a girl
at 4-to-5,</i>

192
00:11:06,957 --> 00:11:08,918
<i>but chances of twins are a long shot.</i>

193
00:11:14,549 --> 00:11:16,217
Herbert!

194
00:11:26,060 --> 00:11:28,145
H.E.R.B.I.E.!

195
00:11:28,229 --> 00:11:29,373
<i>The oil and gas cowboys</i>

196
00:11:29,397 --> 00:11:32,608
want a minute to yell at you
before you go on maternity leave.

197
00:11:32,692 --> 00:11:35,236
Speaking of, coal lobby.

198
00:11:35,736 --> 00:11:37,112
Lynne, when you see Sue, can...

199
00:11:37,196 --> 00:11:39,240
Larry, I will tell her when I see her.

200
00:11:39,324 --> 00:11:40,491
Thank you, Lynne.

201
00:11:40,575 --> 00:11:42,535
The question on everybody's mind is,

202
00:11:42,618 --> 00:11:45,538
"Will the baby be born
with superpowers?"

203
00:11:46,747 --> 00:11:48,183
H.E.R.B.I.E., we need to scan the baby.

204
00:11:48,207 --> 00:11:50,084
The Interna-Scan hasn't achieved

205
00:11:50,167 --> 00:11:52,628
the right level of precession
for clear imaging.

206
00:11:55,047 --> 00:11:57,925
New deep space transmission?

207
00:11:58,008 --> 00:11:59,635
Let's identify its origin.

208
00:11:59,719 --> 00:12:01,637
Shall we record and file it?

209
00:12:01,721 --> 00:12:03,055
<i>Mm-hmm.</i>

210
00:12:08,269 --> 00:12:10,271
2:15? What 2:15?
I don't have any meetings today.

211
00:12:11,439 --> 00:12:12,898
Ah, Reed.

212
00:12:12,982 --> 00:12:14,859
Oh, that 2:15.

213
00:12:14,942 --> 00:12:16,151
Thank you for making the time.

214
00:12:16,235 --> 00:12:17,528
Johnny, do we have to today?

215
00:12:17,612 --> 00:12:19,739
I had some thoughts
on the new suit design.

216
00:12:19,822 --> 00:12:21,616
There are no new suit designs.

217
00:12:21,699 --> 00:12:25,119
You finished them years ago.
They have dust on them.

218
00:12:27,497 --> 00:12:29,415
I get it.
You're going to be a father soon.

219
00:12:29,499 --> 00:12:30,500
New responsibilities.

220
00:12:30,583 --> 00:12:31,852
- You're a bit scared.
- I'm not scared.

221
00:12:31,876 --> 00:12:33,336
I'm busy, Johnny.

222
00:12:33,419 --> 00:12:35,380
I'm busy. I'm busy.

223
00:12:35,463 --> 00:12:37,214
There's a difference.

224
00:12:40,801 --> 00:12:43,178
New transmission today.

225
00:12:44,179 --> 00:12:45,306
Have you listened to it yet?

226
00:12:45,390 --> 00:12:47,558
More of the same. It's a complex signal.

227
00:12:50,227 --> 00:12:52,229
Knock yourself out.

228
00:12:53,773 --> 00:12:56,359
Johnny, I'm running a test.

229
00:12:57,109 --> 00:12:58,403
Cool.

230
00:13:00,696 --> 00:13:01,947
I got time.

231
00:13:03,741 --> 00:13:05,075
Bridge teleportation test.

232
00:13:07,286 --> 00:13:10,373
Movement of organic matter, six meters.

233
00:13:13,000 --> 00:13:14,544
Thank you, Herbert.

234
00:13:16,546 --> 00:13:17,755
Let's run it.

235
00:13:26,096 --> 00:13:27,181
It worked.

236
00:13:30,893 --> 00:13:32,853
- Johnny.
- Yep.

237
00:13:34,146 --> 00:13:35,314
Could you reset the breaker?

238
00:13:40,986 --> 00:13:41,987
Other way.

239
00:14:16,564 --> 00:14:17,648
Babe?

240
00:14:19,149 --> 00:14:20,943
Babe, when you're done, can you...

241
00:14:23,904 --> 00:14:25,948
Hello, H.E.R.B.I.E.

242
00:14:28,367 --> 00:14:31,328
I, um... I just went by the nursery.

243
00:14:33,122 --> 00:14:34,123
How's it looking?

244
00:14:34,206 --> 00:14:38,127
Um, it's looking like
H.E.R.B.I.E.'s building the crib.

245
00:14:38,210 --> 00:14:40,671
Which I kinda thought was a you deal.

246
00:14:40,755 --> 00:14:41,964
I built this instead.

247
00:14:42,047 --> 00:14:45,175
Anyone can build a crib.
Only I can build this.

248
00:14:45,259 --> 00:14:48,554
Anyone can build a crib
but not-not ours. Not for him.

249
00:14:48,638 --> 00:14:50,014
This is for him.

250
00:14:52,266 --> 00:14:53,350
Because unlike anyone else,

251
00:14:53,434 --> 00:14:55,394
his parents have
cosmically compromised DNA.

252
00:14:55,478 --> 00:14:59,398
Reed.
Reed, we have done every test.

253
00:15:00,357 --> 00:15:01,942
